post_text:
Thank you to all who responded!

We asked for your feedback on the preferred format of days in a hybrid learning environment, should we need to enter Tier 3 (orange level) on our Return to School Plan. Currently, we are in Tier 2 (yellow). The survey was sent out August 13th and August 17th the following results were recorded.

The results are as follows:

60.67% = Extended Day Option
39.33% = Alternating Day Option
# of respondents = 89

EXTENDED DAY OPTION: All students attend M-F with K-6 students having classes in the morning (potentially starting the school day earlier than usual) followed by lunch, 7-12 students having lunch followed by classes in the afternoon (potentially ending the school day later than usual).

Sutton Public Schools staff members Hybrid Survey Results showed:
77.1% = Extended Day Option
22.9% = Alternating Day Option

post_text:
Good Afternoon!

As noted in our Return to School Plan, the school district will consider information/data regarding COVID19 from the SHHD, what is occurring in Clay County and most specifically in Sutton to make a determination as to which Tier SPS will be operating at. Page 5 or the Plan speaks to the fluidity of the plan. The Return to School Plan is a blueprint and it provides the framework.

Last evening, SHHD moved the needle of the health risk dial to orange. Based on the information received, Sutton Public Schools will continue to stay with the plan of starting school in Tier II (yellow).

Look forward to seeing you all on the 18th!

Ms. Wiseman

post_text: Laptop Deployment: Starting this school year, we are going to be allowing all 7-12 students to participate in the 1:1 laptop program. This means that all 7-12 students would have the opportunity to take their laptops home. To do so, students and parents/guardians will need to attend our laptop deployment night on Tuesday, August 18th. To help with appropriate social distancing, we ask that families with last name of A-K come at 6:30 pm and families with last name of L-Z come at 7:30 pm. At the meeting, we will cover the expectations, guidelines, and fees for students and their laptops. During that evening, we will be able to collect the $40 laptop insurance fee as well as activity fees, and lunch money. As a reminder, these all need to be separate checks for each of these items. Should you choose to use your personal insurance policy, you must bring a copy of that with you to the meeting for your student to receive their laptop that evening.

Elementary Parents (of K-5th graders):
Today, we planned to send letters about student placements for 2020-2021 home with students. These letters also contain a form to gather parent input with regard to these placements. Obviously sending these letters home with students will not be an option. These letters will be mailed out today, or you can read it here: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1XeqWIVhdve0ohekQTRzNsvxrWMn2B5ox-_tWKUx9jDY/edit?usp=sharing.

You may wait for the letter to arrive in the mail, fill out the form on the back and mail it back to us at school, or you may fill out this form to share your thoughts with us: https://bit.ly/suttonparentinput

Please have your input to us by April 3rd.

post_text: Elementary Families: Members of our transportation department are on the road delivering learning packets to all students this morning. If no one answers the door, these packets will be left at your home. They are also including a letter and the Sutton Elementary School Temporary Distance Learning Plan (TDLP), which will go into effect, should this closure extend beyond this week. If you have questions or concerns, please reach out to the appropriate teacher or to Mr. Carlson (emails can be found in the back of the TDLP or at https://www.suttonpublicschool.org/vnews/display.v/SEC/Staff%7CStaff%20Contact%20Information%3E%3EElementary%20Staff).

Sutton Public Schools WILL be in school tomorrow Tuesday, March 17th as scheduled. Teachers will prepare students for learning at home.

From Wednesday, March 18th through Friday, March 27th, no school or activities at SPS.

School will reconvene on Monday, March, 30th. Please understand that this is a fluid situation and the plan may change due to the coronavirus.

Parents and students will be informed via school social media sites, the school website, or a Code Red Alert will be issued. All staff will report the days students are not in session.

SPS Parents and Students,

Sutton Public Schools is monitoring the developing information related to the spread of COVID-19 (commonly referred to as the coronavirus). The district has reviewed its relevant policies and procedures and is confident that it is prepared to respond to any outbreak of communicable disease that may occur. Should this situation interfere with the district‚Äôs ordinary operations or schedule, you will be provided notice.
We encourage you to remain informed about the spread of the coronavirus, and would recommend that you visit the website for the Department of Health and Human Services, found here, for further information as it develops. We would also encourage you to use this opportunity to remind your students of the importance of getting rest and washing hands, especially during cold and flu season.
Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services
http://dhhs.ne.gov/Pages/Coronavirus.aspx

Ms. Dana Wiseman
Superintendent
Sutton Public Schools

March 4 at 6:25 PM ¬∑

District 6 Career Development Events were held today at CCC in Hastings. Sutton FFA Members worked hard and did a great job today! Results are as follows:

Livestock Management: 3rd place and qualified for state. Tymerie Steinhauer, Joe Hinrichs, Jarvis Smith, Jackson Anderson, and Alyssa Kerwood.

Agronomy: 4th place and qualified for state. Cory Carlson, Dawson Nunnenkamp, Adam Griess, and Jaden Nuss.

Nursery and Landscape: 4th place and qualified for state. Gracie Nuss, Kaleigh Nuss, Carly Rose, and Melaney Nuss.

Meats Evaluation: 6th place. Colby Peterson, Elyzabeth Winter, Sterling Cloet, and Cody Barritt.

Agriscience: 8th place. Tyson Scheidemann, Cason Peterson, Caleb Ladehoff, Noah Gwennap, and Myles Jones.

Farm Business Management: 6th place. Quenton Jones, Andrew Wochner, and Hayden Switzer.

Welding (was held on February 26 in Grand Island): 6th place. Jaden Nuss, Andrew Wochner, Hayden Switzer, and Colby Peterson.

post_text:
At 152 pounds, Joe Hinrichs is 34-1 with 121 career wins. He is a three time state qualifier, earning a bronze medal at state in 2019 and 2020 district champ. Currently Joe is rated as the #1 wrestler in Class C at 152 pounds. Joe has victories over 14 state qualifiers, including 6 district champions this season.

At 285 pounds, Jarvis Smith is 28-10. He is a two time state qualifier, and finished 4th at districts. Jarvis has victories over 5 state qualifiers this season.

Good Luck Joe and Jarvis at State Wrestling this week!!!

It's Friday, and on Fridays we celebrate our hard work and learning from the week! These students are our Mustang Medal winners for this week. They received a bonus in the form of 25 free tickets for the PTO Carnival next Thursday, February 13. We noted the names of the winners this week, and their tickets will be waiting for them at the Carnival. The same is true for anyone who preordered tickets or wristbands. To avoid lost tickets or wristbands, they will not be sent home. All purchases have been recorded, and tickets and wristbands can be picked up the night of the carnival.
Next week's Mustang Medal winners will be drawn on Thursday, and we'll give away more free tickets for the carnival that night!

post_text: GaGa Ball is a HIT!! Thanks to funding and building expertise from the Sutton Elementary PTO, we now have a GaGa Pit for use on indoor recess days. Our amazing custodial crew added some carpet to the bottom of the walls to protect the gym floor, and got it set up for us to start using today, and students LOVED it! If you know a PTO member, be sure to thank them on behalf of our students. If you'd like to be a part of the PTO, please join us for meetings on the second Thursday of every month during the school year at 7:00PM in the elementary library. Lastly, consider supporting their efforts by attending their Carnival Fundraiser & the Title I Family Information Meeting on February 13th, and/or volunteering to help run a carnival game if you are able! Look for notes to come home in backpacks about this BIG event!!
